The Geometry of Autonomous Optimization: A Formal Framework for Semantically Stable, Self‑Improving Systems

Author: ouadi Maakoul 

---

Abstract

This thesis develops a formal, axiomatically grounded framework for autonomous optimization in multi‑agent systems. We define an intent space of verifiable criteria, a system state space with a metric structure, and a knowledge poset representing shared, cumulative expertise. Four axioms capture essential dynamics: an autonomous improvement loop, intent verifiability, transparency, and instantaneous knowledge diffusion. A semantic stability constraint ensures that meaning is preserved across agent transformations. Working on the quotient space of states modulo semantic equivalence, we prove that the evaluation functional converges to its supremum and that the \omega-limit set of the quotient orbit is non‑empty, compact, invariant under all agents, and contained in the maximum evaluation level set. We further show that the precision of intent is the fundamental bottleneck, that knowledge growth accelerates improvement, and that incompatible semantic equivalence relations among agents prevent convergence to a single meaning class. Adding an optional fifth axiom (semantic fixedness at optimality) forces convergence to a common fixed point. The framework provides a rigorous mathematical foundation for analyzing autonomous improvement processes.

---

1. Introduction

The vision of autonomous systems that continuously improve themselves—be they AI agents, robotic fleets, or organizational processes—demands a formal theory that captures the interplay between intent, knowledge, and multi‑agent interaction. Existing approaches in reinforcement learning, multi‑agent systems, and formal verification address fragments of this challenge but lack a unified mathematical structure. This thesis introduces such a structure, which we call The Geometry of Autonomous Optimization.

Our approach models autonomous improvement as a dynamical system on a state space, guided by a verifiable intent and supported by a shared knowledge base. We distill the essential properties into four axioms and a semantic stability constraint. From these, we derive convergence properties, rate bounds, and necessary conditions for multi‑agent stability.

The contributions are purely theoretical:

· A formal definition of the key spaces (intent, state, knowledge) and the axioms that govern autonomous improvement.
· A semantic stability constraint operationalized through closed equivalence relations with evaluation‑invariance.
· A proof of convergence of the evaluation functional and invariance of the limit set in the quotient space.
· Proofs that knowledge diffusion accelerates improvement and that semantic misalignment among agents prevents convergence to a single meaning class.
· An optional fifth axiom that yields convergence to a common semantic fixed point.

The remainder of this thesis is organized as follows. Section 2 presents the mathematical preliminaries and definitions. Section 3 states the axioms and constraints. Section 4 develops the theoretical results, including lemmas, the main theorem, and corollaries. Section 5 concludes.

