2. Mathematical Preliminaries and Definitions

We begin by defining the fundamental objects.

2.1. Intent Space

Let \mathcal{I} be a set of intents. Each intent i\in\mathcal{I} is a statement about desired properties of the system. To be usable in an autonomous optimization loop, intents must be verifiable.

Definition 2.1 (Intent Space).
An intent space is a tuple (\mathcal{I},\preceq,\text{verif}) where:

· \mathcal{I} is a partially ordered set (poset) with order \preceq indicating refinement or sub‑intent relationships.
· For each i\in\mathcal{I}, there exists a verification predicate \text{verif}_i:S\to\{0,1\}, where S is the system state space (defined below), such that \text{verif}_i(s)=1 iff state s satisfies intent i.

We often work with a finite set of atomic intents \{i_1,\dots,i_n\} that are binary (pass/fail). The overall intent I can be a Boolean combination of these atoms. In more general settings, intents may be real‑valued (e.g., “minimize cost”), in which case \text{verif} is replaced by a cost or reward function.

Definition 2.2 (Metric on Intents).
Define a pseudo‑metric \delta:\mathcal{I}\times\mathcal{I}\to\mathbb{R}_{\ge0} by

\delta(I,J)=\sup_{s\in S}|E_I(s)-E_J(s)|,

where E_I is the evaluation function defined below. This captures how close two intents are in terms of their evaluation of system states.

2.2. System State Space

The system evolves over discrete time steps t=0,1,2,\dots. Let S be a compact metric space with distance d_S, representing the set of all possible configurations of the environment, agents, and knowledge artifacts.

Definition 2.3 (System State).
A system state s\in S is a configuration that includes:

· The physical or virtual environment.
· The internal models and parameters of each agent.
· The current knowledge repository (if not separated).

We assume all functions on S are continuous with respect to d_S unless otherwise stated.

2.3. Agents and Schedule

Let \mathcal{A}=\{A_1,A_2,\dots,A_m\} be a finite set of agents. Each agent is a function that maps a state and an intent to a new state.

Definition 2.4 (Agent Function).
An agent A_i:S\times\mathcal{I}\to S is a continuous function. For a given intent I, the agent updates the state:

s' = A_i(s,I).

Definition 2.5 (Fair Schedule).
A schedule \sigma:\mathbb{N}\to\mathcal{A} determines which agent acts at each time step. The schedule is fair if for every agent A_i\in\mathcal{A}, the set \{t\in\mathbb{N}:\sigma(t)=A_i\} is infinite (i.e., each agent acts infinitely often). The evolution is given by:

s_{t+1} = \sigma(t)(s_t,I).

2.4. Evaluation Function

To measure progress, we define an evaluation function that quantifies how well a state fulfills the intent.

Definition 2.6 (Evaluation).
Given an intent I\in\mathcal{I}, let E_I:S\to\mathbb{R} be a bounded, continuous function such that higher values indicate better fulfillment. For atomic intents with binary verification, E_I(s)=\text{verif}_I(s)\in\{0,1\}. For composite intents, E_I may be defined via aggregation (e.g., weighted sum).

2.5. Knowledge Poset

Knowledge is the shared, cumulative expertise that agents can leverage. We model it as a partially ordered set (poset) to capture refinement.

Definition 2.7 (Knowledge Poset).
Let \mathcal{K} be a set of knowledge items equipped with a partial order \preceq_{\mathcal{K}} where k\preceq_{\mathcal{K}}k' means k' refines or strengthens k. A knowledge base is a finite subset K\subset\mathcal{K} that is upward closed with respect to \preceq_{\mathcal{K}} (i.e., if k\in K and k\preceq_{\mathcal{K}}k', then k'\in K).

Agents may extract new knowledge from the current state, producing a knowledge item. The diffusion process is captured by a map that adds the new item and closes under refinement.

Definition 2.8 (Knowledge Extraction and Diffusion).
For each agent A_i and state s, there is a set of extractable knowledge items \text{Extract}_i(s)\subseteq\mathcal{K}. The knowledge base evolves as:

K_{t+1} = \text{Closure}\bigl( K_t \cup \bigcup_{i: \sigma(t)=A_i} \text{Extract}_i(s_t) \bigr),

where \text{Closure} adds all refinements of items already present.

2.6. Semantic Equivalence and Quotient Space

To formalize “preservation of meaning,” we introduce an equivalence relation on states relative to an intent, with the additional requirement that evaluation is invariant on classes.

Definition 2.9 (Semantic Equivalence).
For a given intent I, define a relation \sim_I on S by:

s \sim_I s' \iff \text{for all meaningful attributes }\phi\text{ relevant to }I,\; \phi(s)=\phi(s').

We require that:

1. \sim_I is a closed equivalence relation; i.e., its graph \{(s,s'):s\sim_I s'\} is closed in the product topology of S\times S. Equivalently, the quotient map q_I:S\to S/{\sim_I} is continuous when the quotient carries the quotient topology.
2. Evaluation invariance: E_I is constant on each equivalence class, so it descends to a continuous function \overline{E}_I:Q_I\to\mathbb{R} where Q_I=S/{\sim_I}.

A sufficient condition is the existence of a continuous function \phi_I:S\to\mathbb{R}^k such that s\sim_I s'\iff\phi_I(s)=\phi_I(s'), and E_I factors through \phi_I.

Definition 2.10 (Quotient Dynamics).
Let Q_I = S/{\sim_I} with the quotient topology (compact, as continuous image of compact). By Constraint 1 (below), each agent A_i induces a continuous map \overline{A}_i:Q_I\to Q_I defined by \overline{A}_i([s]) = [A_i(s,I)]. The quotient evolution is q_t = q_I(s_t), and the schedule \sigma acts on Q_I via \overline{A}_{\sigma(t)}.

