3. Axioms and Constraints

We now state the four axioms that define the behavior of the autonomous system, followed by the semantic stability constraint.

Axiom 1 (Autonomous Improvement Loop)

For any fair schedule \sigma, the sequence of states satisfies:

E_I(s_{t+1}) \ge E_I(s_t) - \varepsilon(t),

where \varepsilon(t) is a non‑negative sequence with \sum_{t=0}^\infty \varepsilon(t) < \infty (vanishing error). If \varepsilon(t)=0 for all t, we have monotonic non‑decrease.

Axiom 2 (Intent Verifiability)

Every intent I\in\mathcal{I} can be expressed as a finite Boolean combination of atomic intents i_1,\dots,i_n for which the verification predicate \text{verif}_{i_k} is computable and yields a binary outcome. Consequently, E_I is a computable function of the atomic verification results.

Axiom 3 (Transparency Principle)

For any agent A_i, any state s, and any intent I, the transformation A_i(s,I) and all intermediate data used in computing it are recorded and accessible to all agents (or a trusted monitor). Formally, there exists an observable manifold \mathcal{O} and a projection \pi:S\to\mathcal{O} such that \pi(s) contains all relevant information about s and \pi(A_i(s,I)) is a function of \pi(s). This ensures that the state evolution is fully observable for the purpose of knowledge extraction.

Axiom 4 (Knowledge Diffusion)

Any knowledge extracted by an agent is instantaneously added to the shared knowledge base without loss, as per Definition 2.8. Moreover, for non‑optimal states (where E_I(s) < \sup E_I), at least one agent has a non‑empty extraction set: \bigcup_i \text{Extract}_i(s) \neq \emptyset. This ensures strict knowledge growth until optimality.

Constraint 1 (Semantic Stability)

For any agent A_i, any states s,s'\in S, and any intent I, we have:

s \sim_I s' \implies A_i(s,I) \sim_I A_i(s',I).

In words, agents must map semantically equivalent states (under I) to semantically equivalent outcomes. This prevents meaning from being altered by the optimization process.

Optional Axiom 5 (Semantic Fixedness at Optimality)

If E_I(s)=\sup E_I, then for every agent A_i, A_i(s,I)\sim_I s.

This axiom, when included, forces agents to preserve meaning once the evaluation has reached its maximum. It is natural for systems designed to stabilize at optimal semantic states.

