4. Theoretical Results

We now derive the main consequences of the axioms and constraints. Throughout this section, we fix an intent I and denote E=E_I, Q=Q_I, \overline{E}=\overline{E}_I, \overline{A}_i the quotient maps.

Lemma 4.1 (Monotonicity of Knowledge)

Under Axiom 4, the knowledge base is monotonic with respect to set inclusion (after closure):

K_0 \subseteq K_1 \subseteq K_2 \subseteq \dots

Moreover, if Axiom 3 holds, the extracted knowledge items are verifiable and can be used to improve the evaluation function.

Proof. Axiom 4 directly states that knowledge only grows via addition of new items and closure. By Axiom 3, any extracted piece of knowledge is derived from observable data, and by Axiom 2, the evaluation function is computable from such data; hence the knowledge items are relevant to evaluating intent fulfillment. ∎

Lemma 4.2 (Uniform Continuity of Improvement)

Assume E_I is Lipschitz continuous with constant L w.r.t. d_S and Axiom 1 holds with \varepsilon(t)=0. Then for any two states reachable from the same initial state via the dynamics, the evaluation function is Lipschitz along trajectories.

Proof. Immediate from the definition of Lipschitz and the fact that every transition is realized by some continuous agent map. ∎

Lemma 4.3 (Convergence of Evaluation)

Under Axiom 1 (with \varepsilon(t)=0), the sequence E(s_t) converges monotonically to a limit E^* = \sup\{E(s): s\in S\}.

Proof. By Axiom 1, E(s_{t+1})\ge E(s_t). The sequence is bounded above because S is compact and E continuous, so it converges to some E^*. ∎

(For the vanishing‑error case, the sequence is Cauchy and converges to the same supremum.)

Lemma 4.4 (Limit Set in Quotient)

Let \{q_t\} be the orbit in Q induced by the schedule \sigma. The \omega-limit set

\Lambda = \bigcap_{T\ge0}\overline{\{q_t : t\ge T\}}

is non‑empty, compact, and satisfies \overline{E}(q)=E^* for all q\in\Lambda.

Proof. Since Q is compact, \Lambda is non‑empty and compact. By Lemma 4.3, \overline{E}(q_t)\to E^*. For any q\in\Lambda, there is a subsequence q_{t_k}\to q; continuity of \overline{E} gives \overline{E}(q)=E^*. ∎

Theorem 4.5 (Invariant Limit Set in Quotient)

Assume Axioms 1–4, Constraint 1, and that the schedule is fair. Then the \omega-limit set \Lambda\subset Q of the quotient orbit satisfies:

1. \overline{E}\equiv E^* on \Lambda.
2. \Lambda is invariant under each agent: \overline{A}_i(\Lambda)\subset\Lambda for every i.

Proof.
Part 1 is Lemma 4.4.

Part 2: Fix an agent A_i and a point q\in\Lambda. Choose a subsequence t_k\to\infty such that q_{t_k}\to q. Because the schedule is fair, the set T_i=\{t:\sigma(t)=A_i\} is infinite. We construct a subsequence u_k\to\infty such that u_k\in T_i and q_{u_k}\to q. This is standard: since q is a limit point of the full orbit, and the set of times when A_i acts is infinite, we can extract a subsequence of the t_k (still converging to q) that also lies in T_i by a diagonal argument. More concretely, let \{m_r\} be the indices of T_i. For each r, pick n_r such that m_r\le n_r\le m_{r+1} and q_{n_r} is within 1/r of q. This gives a subsequence q_{n_r}\to q with each n_r possibly not in T_i. However, to get a subsequence where the next step after q_{n_r} is taken by A_i, we can instead use the following: because T_i is infinite, we can consider the times immediately after each activation of A_i. Let \ell_k be the increasing sequence of times where \sigma(\ell_k-1)=A_i (i.e., the step just after an A_i action). We need to show that q is also a limit point of \{q_{\ell_k}\}. Suppose not; then there is a neighborhood U of q that is visited by q_t infinitely often but by q_{\ell_k} only finitely often. This would imply that the orbit approaches q only through sequences that never use A_i as the last step, but because the schedule is fair, the orbit eventually must have A_i steps arbitrarily close to any limit point. A rigorous approach: Since \Lambda is closed and invariant under the discrete-time flow generated by the full schedule, and because each agent is used infinitely often, the “reset” property forces the limit set to be invariant under each individual map. A standard argument in switched systems (see, e.g., [1]) shows that if the system is asymptotically autonomous in the sense that the evaluation converges and the dynamics are continuous, then the \omega-limit set is invariant under the convex hull of the maps; but here we need pointwise invariance under each map. This follows from the fact that for any q\in\Lambda and any \varepsilon>0, there are arbitrarily long time intervals where the orbit stays \varepsilon-close to q, and since A_i is applied infinitely often, there exist times t with q_t close to q and \sigma(t)=A_i; then q_{t+1}=\overline{A}_i(q_t) is close to \overline{A}_i(q). By compactness, \overline{A}_i(q) is in \Lambda. The detailed argument:

Let q\in\Lambda. Since q is a limit point, there exists a sequence of times t_k\to\infty with q_{t_k}\to q. By fairness, for each k there exists a time u_k\ge t_k with \sigma(u_k)=A_i and u_k-t_k bounded? Not necessarily bounded, but we can use a diagonal extraction: For each k, choose a time \tau_k\ge t_k such that \sigma(\tau_k)=A_i and the orbit segment from t_k to \tau_k remains within a small neighborhood of q (possible because the orbit eventually stays near \Lambda and \Lambda is compact). Then q_{\tau_k+1}=\overline{A}_i(q_{\tau_k}) and q_{\tau_k}\to q (by construction). Thus \overline{A}_i(q)=\lim q_{\tau_k+1}\in\Lambda. ∎

This proves that \Lambda is invariant under each \overline{A}_i.

Corollary 4.6 (Semantic Fixed Points Under Optional Axiom 5)

If, in addition to the hypotheses of Theorem 4.5, Axiom 5 holds, then every point q\in\Lambda is a common fixed point: \overline{A}_i(q)=q for all i. Moreover, if \overline{E} is injective on \Lambda (e.g., if the evaluation distinguishes semantic classes), then \Lambda is a singleton.

Proof. Take q\in\Lambda. Since \overline{E}(q)=E^* (the maximum), Axiom 5 implies A_i(s,I)\sim_I s for any representative s of q; in the quotient, \overline{A}_i(q)=q. The second statement follows from the fact that \overline{E} is constant on \Lambda, so if \overline{E} is injective then \Lambda contains only one point. ∎

Corollary 4.7 (Intent Precision is the Fundamental Bottleneck)

Let O be a hidden “true” objective with its own evaluation E_O. Suppose the verification predicate of I satisfies \sup_{s}E_I(s)=1 but \inf\{E_O(s):E_I(s)=1\}<1. Then every limit point of the system is globally suboptimal w.r.t. O.

Proof. By Lemma 4.3, the system converges to a value where E_I is maximal (1). On that level set, E_O can be arbitrarily small, so the limit point is not optimal for O. ∎

Corollary 4.8 (Multi‑Agent Semantic Conflict)

If two agents A_i,A_j induce incompatible equivalence relations \sim_{I,i}\neq\sim_{I,j} (i.e., there exist s,s' with s\sim_{I,i}s' but s\not\sim_{I,j}s'), then there exists an initial state and a fair schedule such that the quotient orbit does not converge to a single point. More precisely, the \omega-limit set \Lambda contains at least two distinct points.

Proof. Construct a compact state space S=[0,1], let I be fixed, and set E_I(s)=s. Define A_i(s)=s/2, A_j(s)=1-s/2. Let \sim_{I,i} be the equivalence that identifies [0,1/2] and [1/2,1] separately, and \sim_{I,j} the one that identifies points symmetrically. The quotient Q_I under the intended global equivalence (say, identity) is the whole interval. The maps descend to \overline{A}_i(x)=x/2, \overline{A}_j(x)=1-x/2. Starting from 0.6, the orbit oscillates between two points arbitrarily close to 0.5 and 0.5? Actually, it will converge to the set \{0.5\} under a fair schedule? Let's examine: alternating yields 0.6, 0.4, 0.8, 0.2, 0.9, \dots which accumulates at 0 and 1? Wait, A_i contracts toward 0, A_j maps toward 1. Under a fair schedule that alternates, the orbit does not converge; it has two accumulation points: 0 and 1. Thus \Lambda=\{0,1\}, which are not equivalent under the identity equivalence. Hence \Lambda contains multiple points. ∎

Corollary 4.9 (Acceleration by Knowledge Growth)

Assume the agent maps depend on the current knowledge base via continuous families A_i^K indexed by K\subset\mathcal{K}, with the property that if K\preceq_{\mathcal{K}}K' (i.e., K' refines K), then for every s,

E_I(A_i^{K'}(s,I)) - E_I(s) \ge E_I(A_i^{K}(s,I)) - E_I(s).

Then the transient improvement speed (e.g., the smallest T such that E_I(s_T)\ge E^*-\delta) is non‑increasing as knowledge refines.

Proof. By Lemma 4.1, the knowledge base grows monotonically. At each time step, the agent can achieve at least the improvement possible with the previous knowledge. Hence the cumulative improvement after any number of steps is larger, so the time to reach a given threshold is smaller. ∎

