5. Conclusion

We have developed a formal, axiomatically grounded framework for autonomous optimization in multi‑agent systems. The framework defines intent, state, knowledge, and agents in precise mathematical terms, and introduces four axioms together with a semantic stability constraint. Working on the quotient space of states modulo semantic equivalence, we proved that the evaluation functional converges to its supremum and that the \omega-limit set of the quotient orbit is non‑empty, compact, invariant under all agents, and contained in the maximum evaluation level set. We identified the precision of intent as the fundamental bottleneck and characterized conditions under which multi‑agent conflicts prevent convergence to a single meaning class. Adding an optional fifth axiom forces convergence to a common semantic fixed point. These results provide a rigorous foundation for analyzing autonomous improvement processes and for designing systems that can reliably progress without losing semantic alignment.

