Appendix A: Topological and Metric Space Background

This appendix collects the necessary topological and metric concepts used throughout the thesis. All spaces are assumed to be Hausdorff unless stated otherwise.

A.1 Compactness

A topological space X is compact if every open cover has a finite subcover. In metric spaces, compactness is equivalent to sequential compactness: every sequence has a convergent subsequence. Compactness is preserved under continuous images: if f:X\to Y is continuous and X compact, then f(X) is compact.

A.2 Quotient Spaces

Let \sim be an equivalence relation on a topological space X. The quotient space X/{\sim} is the set of equivalence classes endowed with the quotient topology: a set U\subset X/{\sim} is open iff its preimage under the quotient map q:X\to X/{\sim} is open in X. The quotient map is continuous and surjective. If \sim is closed (i.e., its graph is closed in X\times X), then X/{\sim} is Hausdorff.

A.3 \omega-Limit Sets

For a sequence \{x_n\} in a compact metric space X, the \omega-limit set is defined as

\omega(\{x_n\}) = \bigcap_{N\ge0} \overline{\{x_n : n\ge N\}}.

It is non‑empty, compact, and consists of all accumulation points of the sequence. If the sequence is generated by a dynamical system, the \omega-limit set often carries invariant properties.

A.4 Continuity and Lipschitz Maps

A map f:X\to Y between metric spaces is Lipschitz if there exists L\ge0 such that d_Y(f(x),f(x'))\le L\,d_X(x,x') for all x,x'. Lipschitz maps are uniformly continuous. Lipschitz constants are submultiplicative under composition.

