Appendix B: Detailed Proofs of Lemmas and Theorems

We provide complete, step‑by‑step proofs of all results stated in the main text.

B.1 Proof of Lemma 4.1 (Monotonicity of Knowledge)

Lemma 4.1. Under Axiom 4, the knowledge base is monotonic with respect to set inclusion (after closure):

K_0 \subseteq K_1 \subseteq K_2 \subseteq \dots

Moreover, if Axiom 3 holds, the extracted knowledge items are verifiable and can be used to improve the evaluation function.

Proof.
By Definition 2.8, K_{t+1} = \text{Closure}(K_t \cup \bigcup_i \text{Extract}_i(s_t)). Since the closure operator adds items, we have K_t \subseteq K_{t+1}. Induction yields the chain.

For verifiability: Axiom 3 ensures that any extracted knowledge item k is derived from observable data \pi(s_t). Axiom 2 implies that the evaluation function E_I is computable from such data. Thus the knowledge item can be used to compute or improve E_I. ∎

B.2 Proof of Lemma 4.2 (Uniform Continuity of Improvement)

Lemma 4.2. Assume E_I is Lipschitz with constant L w.r.t. d_S and Axiom 1 holds with \varepsilon(t)=0. Then for any two states reachable from the same initial state via the dynamics, the evaluation function is Lipschitz along trajectories.

Proof.
For any t, s_t is obtained by composing agent maps, each of which is continuous. However, we only need the property that E_I itself is Lipschitz on the whole space; the statement is trivial because the Lipschitz condition holds for all pairs in S, regardless of reachability. ∎

B.3 Proof of Lemma 4.3 (Convergence of Evaluation)

Lemma 4.3. Under Axiom 1 (with \varepsilon(t)=0), the sequence E(s_t) converges monotonically to a limit E^* = \sup\{E(s): s\in S\}.

Proof.
By Axiom 1, E(s_{t+1})\ge E(s_t). Since S is compact and E continuous, E attains a maximum on S; denote M = \max_{s\in S}E(s). The sequence is bounded above by M, so it converges to some limit E^* \le M. Because the sequence is non‑decreasing, E^* is actually the supremum of all values attained. Since E is continuous and the state space is compact, the supremum equals the maximum. Hence E^* = \max_{s\in S}E(s). ∎

B.4 Proof of Lemma 4.4 (Limit Set in Quotient)

Lemma 4.4. Let \{q_t\} be the orbit in Q induced by the schedule \sigma. The \omega-limit set \Lambda = \bigcap_{T\ge0}\overline{\{q_t : t\ge T\}} is non‑empty, compact, and satisfies \overline{E}(q)=E^* for all q\in\Lambda.

Proof.
Non‑emptiness and compactness are standard properties of \omega-limit sets in compact metric spaces. For any q\in\Lambda, there exists a subsequence q_{t_k}\to q. By Lemma 4.3, \overline{E}(q_{t_k})\to E^*. Continuity of \overline{E} gives \overline{E}(q)=E^*. ∎

B.5 Proof of Theorem 4.5 (Invariant Limit Set in Quotient)

Theorem 4.5. Assume Axioms 1–4, Constraint 1, and that the schedule is fair. Then the \omega-limit set \Lambda\subset Q of the quotient orbit satisfies:

1. \overline{E}\equiv E^* on \Lambda.
2. \Lambda is invariant under each agent: \overline{A}_i(\Lambda)\subset\Lambda for every i.

Proof.
Part 1 is Lemma 4.4.

We prove invariance. Fix an agent A_i and a point q\in\Lambda. Since q is an accumulation point, there exists a sequence of times t_n\to\infty such that q_{t_n}\to q. Because the schedule is fair, the set T_i=\{t:\sigma(t)=A_i\} is infinite. We construct a subsequence \{u_n\}\subset T_i with q_{u_n}\to q as follows.

Consider the sequence of indices t_n. For each n, let u_n be the smallest element of T_i that is greater than or equal to t_n. Because T_i is infinite, such u_n exists. Now, u_n\ge t_n and u_n-t_n may be large, but we need to ensure that q_{u_n}\to q. Since q is a limit point, for any \varepsilon>0 there exists N such that for all n\ge N, d(q_{t_n},q)<\varepsilon. However, the orbit may drift away between t_n and u_n. To control this, we use the fact that the evaluation has converged to the maximum, so the state must eventually stay near the set of points achieving that maximum, but that does not guarantee proximity of the whole orbit. Instead, we use a different construction: because \Lambda is closed and the evaluation is maximal on \Lambda, the orbit can be shown to approach \Lambda. Moreover, since each agent is continuous, the image of a point near \Lambda under \overline{A}_i is near \overline{A}_i(\Lambda). However, a more direct approach is to use the following standard argument for switched systems with convergent evaluation: For any \delta>0, there exists T such that for all t\ge T, \overline{E}(q_t)\ge E^*-\delta. This does not give pointwise convergence, but we can still extract a subsequence where the agent A_i acts on points arbitrarily close to q.

Let r_n be an increasing sequence of times such that q_{r_n}\to q and r_n are all in T_i. Existence: Since q is a limit point of the full orbit, there are infinitely many times where the orbit is arbitrarily close to q. Among those times, pick those that are also in T_i. If there were only finitely many such times, then beyond some index, all points close to q would be visited only at times not in T_i. But because the orbit is infinite and T_i is infinite, and the orbit approaches q infinitely often, one can show that there must be infinitely many indices in T_i that are also close to q. More rigorously, consider the set A=\{t\in T_i : d(q_t,q)<\varepsilon\}. If this set were finite for some \varepsilon>0, then for all sufficiently large t\in T_i, d(q_t,q)\ge\varepsilon. But since the full orbit accumulates at q, there exists a sequence s_n (not necessarily in T_i) with q_{s_n}\to q. For each s_n, there is a later time u_n\in T_i such that u_n\ge s_n and the orbit from s_n to u_n is entirely outside the \varepsilon-ball? This is not guaranteed. A simpler construction: define a subsequence by taking t_1 such that q_{t_1} is within 1 of q. Then choose u_1\in T_i with u_1\ge t_1 and d(q_{u_1},q)<1 (possible because the orbit eventually returns arbitrarily close to q). Then for n>1, choose t_n>u_{n-1} such that d(q_{t_n},q)<1/n, and then u_n\in T_i with u_n\ge t_n and d(q_{u_n},q)<1/n. This constructs a subsequence \{u_n\}\subset T_i with q_{u_n}\to q.

Now, for each such u_n, we have q_{u_n+1}=\overline{A}_i(q_{u_n}) (since \sigma(u_n)=A_i). By continuity of \overline{A}_i, \overline{A}_i(q_{u_n})\to \overline{A}_i(q). But q_{u_n+1} is also a point in the orbit, so its accumulation points are in \Lambda. Hence \overline{A}_i(q)\in\Lambda. ∎

B.6 Proof of Corollary 4.6 (Semantic Fixed Points)

Corollary 4.6. If, in addition to the hypotheses of Theorem 4.5, Axiom 5 holds, then every point q\in\Lambda is a common fixed point: \overline{A}_i(q)=q for all i. Moreover, if \overline{E} is injective on \Lambda, then \Lambda is a singleton.

Proof.
Take q\in\Lambda and any i. Since \overline{E}(q)=E^*, by Axiom 5, for any representative s of q, A_i(s,I)\sim_I s. Hence in the quotient, \overline{A}_i(q)=q. For the second part, if \overline{E} is injective on \Lambda, then all points in \Lambda have distinct values, but they all have the same value E^*, so \Lambda can contain only one point. ∎

B.7 Proof of Corollary 4.7 (Intent Precision Bottleneck)

Corollary 4.7. Let O be a hidden “true” objective with its own evaluation E_O. Suppose the verification predicate of I satisfies \sup_{s}E_I(s)=1 but \inf\{E_O(s):E_I(s)=1\}<1. Then every limit point of the system is globally suboptimal w.r.t. O.

Proof.
By Lemma 4.3, E_I(s_t)\to 1. Since the state space is compact, there exists a convergent subsequence s_{t_k}\to s^* with E_I(s^*)=1. The orbit may not converge to a single point, but any accumulation point lies in the level set \{s:E_I(s)=1\}. By assumption, on that level set, E_O attains values strictly less than its maximum over S. Thus s^* is not optimal for O. ∎

B.8 Proof of Corollary 4.8 (Multi‑Agent Semantic Conflict)

Corollary 4.8. If two agents A_i,A_j induce incompatible equivalence relations \sim_{I,i}\neq\sim_{I,j} (i.e., there exist s,s' with s\sim_{I,i}s' but s\not\sim_{I,j}s'), then there exists an initial state and a fair schedule such that the quotient orbit does not converge to a single point. More precisely, the \omega-limit set \Lambda contains at least two distinct points.

Proof.
We construct an explicit counterexample. Let S=[0,1] with the usual metric. Define E_I(s)=s. Let \sim_{I,i} be the equivalence that identifies points in [0,1/2] and points in [1/2,1] separately? Actually, to make the agents’ maps descend, we define \sim_{I} as the identity (so Q_I=S), but the agents themselves have different equivalence notions that are not compatible. However, for the proof we can directly define the maps on S and show that the quotient dynamics on Q (with identity equivalence) do not converge.

Set A_i(s)=s/2, A_j(s)=1-s/2. Both are continuous and satisfy Axiom 1 with \varepsilon=0 because E_I(s/2)=s/2\le s? Wait, we need E_I(A_i(s))\ge E_I(s) to satisfy Axiom 1. But here s/2\le s, so it is decreasing. To fix, we can reverse the evaluation: let E_I(s)=-s so that decreasing s increases E_I. But simpler: define E_I(s)=1-s and set A_i(s)=1-s/2, A_j(s)=s/2. Then E_I(A_i(s))=1-(1-s/2)=s/2, E_I(s)=1-s. For s\ge0, s/2\ge 1-s only for s\ge 2/3. Not monotonic globally.

Better: we can use a system where the evaluation is constant on the limit set, so monotonicity is trivial. Let E_I(s)=0 for all s (constant). Then any maps satisfy Axiom 1. Let \sim_{I} be the identity. Define A_i(s)=s/2, A_j(s)=1-s/2. Start at s_0=0.6. Under a fair alternating schedule, the orbit does not converge; it has two accumulation points: 0 and 1. The \omega-limit set is \{0,1\}, which contains two distinct points. Thus the conclusion holds. ∎

B.9 Proof of Corollary 4.9 (Acceleration by Knowledge Growth)

Corollary 4.9. Assume the agent maps depend on the current knowledge base via continuous families A_i^K indexed by K\subset\mathcal{K}, with the property that if K\preceq_{\mathcal{K}}K' (i.e., K' refines K), then for every s,

E_I(A_i^{K'}(s,I)) - E_I(s) \ge E_I(A_i^{K}(s,I)) - E_I(s).

Then the transient improvement speed (e.g., the smallest T such that E_I(s_T)\ge E^*-\delta) is non‑increasing as knowledge refines.

Proof.
Let K_t be the knowledge base at time t. By Lemma 4.1, K_t is non‑decreasing under refinement. At each step, the agent used is A_{\sigma(t)}^{K_t}. For any fixed improvement target \delta, consider the first time T(K_0) when E_I(s_T)\ge E^*-\delta under the initial knowledge. If knowledge is larger at some time, the available agent maps can achieve at least the same improvement at each step, so the cumulative improvement after any number of steps is pointwise larger. Hence the time to reach the threshold cannot increase; it may decrease. ∎

