Appendix D: Additional Mathematical Tools

D.1 Posets and Closure Operators

A poset (P,\le) is a set with a reflexive, antisymmetric, transitive relation. A closure operator on a poset is a map c:P\to P that is extensive (x\le c(x)), monotone (x\le y\Rightarrow c(x)\le c(y)), and idempotent (c(c(x))=c(x)). In our knowledge setting, the closure that adds all refinements is a closure operator on the power set of \mathcal{K} ordered by inclusion.

D.2 Compactness in Quotient Spaces

If X is compact and \sim is a closed equivalence relation, then X/{\sim} is compact and Hausdorff. This ensures the quotient dynamics are well‑behaved.

D.3 Switched Systems and Limit Sets

For a family of continuous maps f_i:X\to X on a compact metric space X, and a switching signal \sigma:\mathbb{N}\to\{1,\dots,m\}, the trajectory is x_{t+1}=f_{\sigma(t)}(x_t). The \omega-limit set is invariant under the set of maps \{f_i\} in the sense that for every x\in\omega, there exists a sequence of indices such that f_{i_k}(x_k)\to f_i(x) for some i. A stronger invariance property holds if the signal is “dwell‑time” or “fair” and the maps satisfy certain conditions. Theorem 4.5 gives invariance under each individual map under fairness and convergent evaluation.

