Appendix E: Optional Extensions (Sketch)

This appendix outlines possible extensions that could be developed in future work.

E.1 Stochastic Schedules and Agents

If the schedule is a random process (e.g., each agent chosen independently with positive probability), one can prove almost‑sure convergence using martingale methods. The evaluation function becomes a submartingale, and the limit set is invariant with probability 1.

E.2 Continuous‑Time Limit

Define a differential inclusion \dot{s} \in F_I(s) where F_I(s) = \{\lim_{h\to0} (A_i(s,I)-s)/h : i=1,\dots,m\} (if the agents can be interpreted as time‑scaled). Under Lipschitz assumptions, the system converges to an equilibrium set where \dot{s}=0 and semantic stability holds. The quotient dynamics become a flow on Q_I.

E.3 Evolving Intents

Allow the intent to change over time based on knowledge. One can model a hierarchy of intents \mathcal{I}_t with refinement maps. The evaluation function then becomes time‑dependent, and the convergence theorem may be adapted using a Lyapunov‑like function that incorporates intent drift.

E.4 Categorical Formulation

View the state space as a fibration over the intent poset. Agents become functors preserving the fibration (i.e., cartesian morphisms). This perspective yields free theorems about composition and modular design of autonomous systems.

